<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>31.</strong> Hillary Diane Rodham Clinton, who sacrificed personal ambition for her husbandâs political career and then rose to be a globally influential figure, became the first woman to accept a major partyâs presidential nomination on July 28, a prize that generations of American women have dreamed about for one of their own. Declaring that the nation was at âa moment of reckoning,â Mrs. Clinton urged voters to reject the divisive policy ideas and combative politics of the Republican nominee, Donald J. Trump. But demonstrations inside and outside the convention hall made clear that Mrs. Clinton has some work to do to persuade at least some die-hard supporters of <a href="//www.nytimes.com/video/us/politics/100000004551621/sanders-supporters-throw-convention-into-disarray.html">_________</a>. </p>
